:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holcombe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Holcomb  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Holcomb","meanings":["English (Surrey and Sussex): habitational name from any of several places called Holcombe (Devon, Dorset, Gloucestershire, Lancashire, Oxfordshire, Somerset), from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jane De Holcombe was born about 1372, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Lord Walter Holcombe. She died in 1435, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1372–1435":"umbes 1372–1435","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1385–1419":"1385–1419","1372–1435":"1372–1435","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1435":"1435","1368":"1368","1385":"1385","1372":"1372","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1419":"1419","about 1372":"umbes 1372","1428":"1428","Hull, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Hole, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1372–1435":"noin 1372–1435","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1385–1419":"1385–1419","1372–1435":"1372–1435","about 1428":"noin 1428","1435":"1435","1368":"1368","1385":"1385","1372":"1372","about 1385":"noin 1385","1419":"1419","about 1372":"noin 1372","1428":"1428","Hull, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Hole, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1372–1435":"environ 1372–1435","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1385–1419":"1385–1419","1372–1435":"1372–1435","about 1428":"environ 1428","1435":"1435","1368":"1368","1385":"1385","1372":"1372","about 1385":"environ 1385","1419":"1419","about 1372":"environ 1372","1428":"1428","Hull, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","Hole, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Jane De Holcombe est née environ 1372, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lord Walter Holcombe. Elle est décédée en 1435, à l’âge de 64 ans."},"de":{"about 1372–1435":"um 1372–1435","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1385–1419":"1385–1419","1372–1435":